00:00:51.735 --> 00:00:52.568
(contemplative music)

00:00:52.568 --> 00:00:54.060
Around 300 BC,

00:00:54.060 --> 00:00:57.570
the Greek mathematician, Euclid,
takes on a massive project

00:00:57.570 --> 00:01:00.840
to summarize all mathematics
known at the time,

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:02.700
to essentially create the one book

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:04.230
that contains everything

00:01:04.230 --> 00:01:07.290
that everyone knows about mathematics.

00:01:07.290 --> 00:01:09.330
But that's no easy task.

00:01:09.330 --> 00:01:13.320
See, before Euclid, there was
a bit of a problem with math.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:15.000
- People would prove things,

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:16.507
but they would just be
going around in circles.

00:01:16.507 --> 00:01:18.517
"Why does a triangle have 180 degrees?"

00:01:18.517 --> 00:01:19.747
"'Cause if you take two parallel lines -"

00:01:19.747 --> 00:01:21.067
"Yeah, but why do parallel lines exist?"

00:01:21.067 --> 00:01:22.537
"Oh, that's because you can make a square.

00:01:22.537 --> 00:01:23.580
"Why does a square exist?"

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:24.840
You have this infinite recursion

00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:29.280
of what the fundamental reason
why something is true is.

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:30.810
- [Derek] It's kind of
like in the dictionary,

00:01:30.810 --> 00:01:33.960
every word is defined
in terms of other words,

00:01:33.960 --> 00:01:35.973
so how do you get to ground truth?

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:40.680
Euclid used a solution that
was pioneered by the Greeks.

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:44.790
Let's just accept a few of
the most simple, basic things

00:01:44.790 --> 00:01:48.180
as being true, these are our postulates.

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:49.980
Then, based upon these postulates,

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:52.440
we can prove theorems one at a time,

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:54.630
building up our math using logic,

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:57.150
so that as long as those
first statements are true,

00:01:57.150 --> 00:01:59.340
then everything else
that follows from them

00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:02.100
must definitely be true.

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:04.470
He had perfected the gold standard

00:02:04.470 --> 00:02:06.480
for rigorous mathematical proof

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:08.793
that all modern math relies on.

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:11.340
Euclid used this method

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:14.790
when he published his 13 book
series called, "The Elements,"

00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:17.670
in which he proved 465 theorems,

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:20.700
covering almost all of
mathematics known at the time,

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:23.133
including geometry and number theory.

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:27.600
And all these theorems depended
on were some definitions,

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:30.603
a few common notions, and five postulates.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:34.590
- We go right to book one,

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:36.150
and book one starts with definitions,

00:02:36.150 --> 00:02:37.290
you gotta start somewhere.

00:02:37.290 --> 00:02:38.123
And the definition is,

00:02:38.123 --> 00:02:40.290
"A point is that which has no part.

00:02:40.290 --> 00:02:42.360
A line is a breadthless length."

00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:45.270
And, "The ends of lines are points."

00:02:45.270 --> 00:02:47.310
By line, he really means a curve,

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:48.937
and then it has some ends.

00:02:48.937 --> 00:02:51.840
"A straight line is a
line that lies evenly

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:53.880
within the points on itself."

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:55.650
And then so on, and so forth.

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:57.540
He's got 23 definitions,

00:02:57.540 --> 00:02:58.993
then he's got the five postulates.

00:02:58.993 --> 00:03:00.450
(energetic music)

00:03:00.450 --> 00:03:02.490
- [Derek] The first four are simple.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:04.350
One, if you have two points,

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:06.780
you can draw a straight line between them.

00:03:06.780 --> 00:03:08.490
Two, if you have a straight line,

00:03:08.490 --> 00:03:11.040
you can extend it indefinitely.

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:15.390
Three, given a center and a
radius, you can draw a circle.

00:03:15.390 --> 00:03:17.820
And the fourth is that all right angles

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:19.710
are equal to each other.

00:03:19.710 --> 00:03:21.780
- [Alex] But postulate
five gets the big guns.

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:22.920
- [Derek] Which is that,

00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:25.530
if a straight line falling
