as a 24 page appendix

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:28.683
to his father's textbook.

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:32.730
Extremely proud and excited
about his son's work,

00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:33.990
Farkas Bolyai sent it

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:36.630
to perhaps the greatest
mathematician of all time,

00:11:36.630 --> 00:11:39.150
Carl Friedrich Gauss.

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:40.710
After careful examination,

00:11:40.710 --> 00:11:42.547
Gauss replied a few months later,

00:11:42.547 --> 00:11:45.990
"To praise it would
amount to praising myself

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:48.750
for the entire content of the work

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:52.080
coincides almost exactly
with my own meditations,

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:55.925
which have occupied my mind
for the past 30 or 35 years."

00:11:55.925 --> 00:11:56.790
(soft music)

00:11:56.790 --> 00:12:00.090
Years earlier, Gauss had
wandered a similar path.

00:12:00.090 --> 00:12:03.300
In 1824, he wrote a private
letter to one of his friends,

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:06.990
in which he describes
discovering a curious geometry,

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:10.080
one with paradoxical,
and to the uninitiated,

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:11.763
absurd theorems.

00:12:12.840 --> 00:12:14.407
For example, Gauss writes,

00:12:14.407 --> 00:12:16.290
"The three angles of a triangle

00:12:16.290 --> 00:12:18.720
become as small as one wishes,

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:21.750
if only the sides are taken large enough.

00:12:21.750 --> 00:12:23.460
Yet the area of the triangle

00:12:23.460 --> 00:12:26.640
can never exceed a definite limit."

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:27.570
In other words,

00:12:27.570 --> 00:12:30.540
you can have a triangle
that's infinitely long,

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:32.463
but the area is finite.

00:12:33.570 --> 00:12:36.600
You can see why by using
the Poincare disk model.

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:39.030
A small triangle looks pretty ordinary,

00:12:39.030 --> 00:12:40.740
but as you make it bigger,

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:44.250
the angles start to become
smaller and smaller.

00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:46.950
Eventually, all those angles go to zero,

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:51.090
because all these lines
intersect the disk at 90 degrees.

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:53.550
Now, these lines are infinitely long,

00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:57.213
but because of the geometry,
the area is finite.

00:12:59.040 --> 00:13:01.237
In the same private letter, Gauss wrote,

00:13:01.237 --> 00:13:03.690
"All my efforts to
discover a contradiction

00:13:03.690 --> 00:13:07.440
and inconsistency in this
non-Euclidean geometry

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:10.200
have been without success."

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:12.960
Just like Bolyai, Gauss had
found that this geometry

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:15.150
seemed thoroughly consistent.

00:13:15.150 --> 00:13:17.490
He named it non-Euclidean geometry,

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:18.960
a name that stuck.

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:20.160
It describes geometries

00:13:20.160 --> 00:13:22.410
where Euclid's first four postulates hold,

00:13:22.410 --> 00:13:24.270
but the fifth doesn't.

00:13:24.270 --> 00:13:26.430
But Gauss decided not
to publish his findings

00:13:26.430 --> 00:13:28.023
for fear of ridicule.

00:13:29.130 --> 00:13:31.800
This aversion to a
different kind of geometry

00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:33.900
should at least be a little surprising,

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:35.910
because there is one other geometry

00:13:35.910 --> 00:13:39.330
that we should be very familiar
with, spherical geometry,

00:13:39.330 --> 00:13:41.957
since we all live on a sphere.

00:13:41.957 --> 00:13:42.790
(soft music)

00:13:42.790 --> 00:13:46.050
On a sphere, straight lines
are parts of great circles,

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:47.040
these are the circles

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:49.440
with the largest possible circumference.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:52.110
On Earth, the equator,
and circles of longitude,

00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:54.123
are examples of great circles,

00:13:55.140 --> 00:13:58.470
and we can use this to see
how straight lines behave.

00:13:58.470 --> 00:14:01.170
These lines seem to go
in the same direction,

00:14:01.170 --> 00:14:02.760
but as you keep extending them,

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:05.580
you find that they intersect once,

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:08.550
and then again on the
other side of the earth.

00:14:08.550 --> 00:14:12.030
And this will always happen
for any two great circles,

00:14:12.030 --> 00:14:13.530
because they must each

00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:15.750
have the largest possible circumference,

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:19.653
so, on a sphere, there
are no parallel lines.

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:24.240
Gauss had long been fascinated
by spherical geometry.

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:25.800
He was also a geodesist,

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:27.860
and frequently took
measurements of the Earth.

00:14:27.860 --> 00:14:29.130
In the 1820s,

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:31.980
he was tasked with surveying
the Kingdom of Hanover

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:33.690
to help make a map.

00:14:33.690 --> 00:14:34.650
As part of this survey,

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:36.960
he climbed the mountains near Gottingen.

00:14:36.960 --> 00:14:39.330
With the help of people
situated on other landmarks,

00:14:39.330 --> 00:14:41.430
they were able to carefully
measure the angles

00:14:41.430 --> 00:14:43.110
of several triangles,

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:45.240
which would then be used
to determine the position

00:14:45.240 --> 00:14:47.490
of one place relative to another.

00:14:47.490 --> 00:14:48.930
As a reference for the survey,

00:14:48.930 --> 00:14:51.570
and to help determine the
roundness of the Earth,

00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:54.930
they also precisely measured
the angles of a large triangle

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:56.703
formed by three mountains.

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:00.780
But for all of Gauss' romantic notions

00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:02.882
of taking measurements
on top of mountains,

00:15:02.882 --> 00:15:03.715
(contemplative music)

00:15:03.715 --> 00:15:06.210
he was not the kindest correspondent.

00:15:06.210 --> 00:15:08.700
When Bolyai received his hero's response,

00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:10.230
he was devastated,

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:12.300
believing that Gauss was
trying to undermine him

00:15:12.300 --> 00:15:14.190
and steal his ideas.

00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:16.710
He was so embittered by Gauss' response

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:19.083
that he never published again.

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:23.460
In 1848, Bolyai had to
endure another hardship

00:15:23.460 --> 00:15:25.410
when he found out that
Russian mathematician,

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:26.790
Nikolai Lobachevsky,

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:29.850
had independently discovered
non-Euclidean geometry,

00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:32.310
several years before Bolyai had published

00:15:32.310 --> 00:15:34.713
his 24 page long appendix.

00:15:36.030 --> 00:15:38.250
When Bolyai died in 1860,

00:15:38.250 --> 00:15:40.740
he left behind 20,000 pages

00:15:40.740 --> 00:15:43.380
of unpublished mathematical manuscripts.

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:44.430
He would not know

00:15:44.430 --> 00:15:46.650
that Gauss did independently discover

00:15:46.650 --> 00:15:48.330
non-Euclidean geometry,

00:15:48.330 --> 00:15:50.640
nor would he know, that
upon receiving the appendix,

00:15:50.640 --> 00:15:52.867
Gauss had written to a friend,

00:15:52.867 --> 00:15:55.440
"I regard this young geometer, Bolyai,

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:58.932
as a genius of the first order."

00:15:58.932 --> 00:16:01.290
(soft music)

00:16:01.290 --> 00:16:03.030
While Bolyai was embittered,

00:16:03.030 --> 00:16:06.360
non-Euclidean geometries
continued to develop.

00:16:06.360 --> 00:16:10.650
Until 1854, spherical geometry
wasn't actually considered

00:16:10.650 --> 00:16:13.050
a non-Euclidean geometry.

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:14.760
That's because, on a sphere,

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:17.610
lines can't be extended indefinitely.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:19.950
This is what earlier
mathematicians had stumbled upon,

00:16:19.950 --> 00:16:21.990
and therefore dismissed this geometry,

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:25.530
since Euclid's second
postulate wouldn't hold.

00:16:25.530 --> 00:16:27.120
But in 1854,

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:29.160
Riemann changed the second postulate

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:31.050
from an infinite extension

00:16:31.050 --> 00:16:33.690
to something that is, quote, "unbounded,"

00:16:33.690 --> 00:16:36.933
so that the second postulate
still holds on a sphere.

00:16:38.160 --> 00:16:40.680
With this change,
spherical geometry became

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:43.590
another valid non-Euclidean geometry.

00:16:43.590 --> 00:16:45.930
By using the generalized four postulates,

00:16:45.930 --> 00:16:48.960
and taking the fifth as there
being no parallel lines,

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:52.623
you could now derive spherical
or elliptic geometry.

00:16:53.850 --> 00:16:56.973
Would you consider the
fifth postulate a mistake?

00:16:57.870 --> 00:17:00.570
Would it have been better if
he just never wrote that down?

00:17:00.570 --> 00:17:01.740
- If he never wrote that down,

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:03.060
he would've stunted his geometry,

00:17:03.060 --> 00:17:04.320
'cause he wouldn't be able to prove

00:17:04.320 --> 00:17:06.600
a lot of things that he claimed to have.

00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:09.270
It's beautiful that he wrote this.

00:17:09.270 --> 00:17:11.580
It's beautiful that
people spent 2,000 years

00:17:11.580 --> 00:17:12.810
trying to refute him,

00:17:12.810 --> 00:17:15.900
only to discover that,
in fact, he was right

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:18.270
in writing this in the first place.

00:17:18.270 --> 00:17:20.040
- [Derek] So, while Euclid was right

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:21.720
to write down the fifth postulate,

00:17:21.720 --> 00:17:24.600
he did make a different mistake.

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:26.670
- So here's the problem
with what Euclid was doing.

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:30.540
Definition 1, "A point is
that which has no part."

00:17:30.540 --> 00:17:31.740
What does it mean to have a part?

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:33.090
What is a part?

00:17:33.090 --> 00:17:34.267
What does it mean not to have a part?

00:17:34.267 --> 00:17:37.350
"A line is a breadthless length."

00:17:37.350 --> 00:17:38.640
What does it mean to have breadth?

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:40.230
Lying evenly within itself,

00:17:40.230 --> 00:17:41.700
within the points on itself?

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:43.110
What the hell is he talking about?

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:44.820
We read this two minutes ago,

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:45.757
and we were nodding along like,

00:17:45.757 --> 00:17:48.120
"Yeah, completely makes
sense what he's saying."

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:49.350
It's all nonsense.

00:17:49.350 --> 00:17:51.150
Don't give me a definition

00:17:51.150 --> 00:17:53.340
that's gonna have an infinite recursion.

00:17:53.340 --> 00:17:55.320
If you give me a definition
in terms of other things,

00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:56.880
then you have to tell me
what those things are.

00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:57.713
If you tell me what that is,

00:17:57.713 --> 00:17:59.820
you have to tell me what
the thing before it is.

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:02.970
- Are the definitions a bad idea?

00:18:02.970 --> 00:18:05.160
- You shouldn't have definitions,

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:07.170
you should have undefined terms.

00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:08.580
I'm not gonna tell you what a point is,

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:09.720
I'm not gonna tell you what a line is,

00:18:09.720 --> 00:18:11.430
I'm not gonna tell you what a plane is.

00:18:11.430 --> 00:18:14.880
All I'm gonna tell you is
what the postulates are

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:16.530
that they're assumed to satisfy.

00:18:16.530 --> 00:18:19.530
It's the relationships between
the objects that's important,

00:18:19.530 --> 00:18:21.990
not the definitions of
the objects themselves.

00:18:21.990 --> 00:18:25.050
And once you free your
mind to that possibility,

00:18:25.050 --> 00:18:26.070
all of a sudden,

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:29.160
you realize that there's a
perfectly good geometric world

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:31.710
in which, by line, you mean great circle,

00:18:31.710 --> 00:18:33.600
and by plane, you mean sphere,

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:36.540
and by point, you mean
a point on a sphere,

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:39.210
and then four of those
axioms are satisfied,

00:18:39.210 --> 00:18:40.560
just not the fifth.

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:42.930
And similarly, there's another model,

00:18:42.930 --> 00:18:45.570
something called a disk
model for hyperbolic space,

00:18:45.570 --> 00:18:47.283
which, the disk is the plane.

00:18:48.570 --> 00:18:49.950
What I mean by straight lines

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:52.890
is arcs of circles that
are orthogonal to the disk,

00:18:52.890 --> 00:18:55.620
and then points are
points inside the disk.

00:18:55.620 --> 00:18:56.920
And the disk is the plane.

00:18:58.200 --> 00:19:00.400
- [Derek] See, you can
think of geometry as a game.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:01.233
(thoughtful music)

00:19:01.233 --> 00:19:02.066
The first four postulates

00:19:02.066 --> 00:19:05.250
are like the minimum rules
required to play that game,

00:19:05.250 --> 00:19:06.810
and then the fifth postulate

00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:09.720
selects the world that you'll play in.

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:11.610
If you pick that there
are no parallel lines,

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:13.740
you're playing in spherical geometry.

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:15.660
If you choose one parallel line,

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:17.490
you're playing in flat geometry.

00:19:17.490 --> 00:19:19.890
And if you go for more
than one parallel line,

00:19:19.890 --> 00:19:22.353
then you're playing in
hyperbolic geometry.

00:19:23.730 --> 00:19:26.640
But Riemann decided to
take it one step further.

00:19:26.640 --> 00:19:29.430
Instead of selecting just
one world to play in,

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:31.893
why not combine them all into one?

00:19:33.330 --> 00:19:35.910
During his inaugural speech in 1854,

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:38.010
he laid out the groundwork for a geometry

00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:41.040
where the curvature could
differ from place to place.

00:19:41.040 --> 00:19:42.510
One part might be flat,

00:19:42.510 --> 00:19:44.490
another part might be slightly curved,

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:47.820
and yet another part might
have a very strong curvature.

00:19:47.820 --> 00:19:49.710
And this geometry wouldn't be limited

00:19:49.710 --> 00:19:51.780
to two-dimensional planes either,

00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:55.173
it could be extended to
three or more dimensions.

00:19:56.623 --> 00:19:57.570
(contemplative music)

00:19:57.570 --> 00:20:00.000
Another breakthrough came in 1868,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.640
when Eugenio Beltrami unequivocally proved

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:04.830
that hyperbolic and spherical geometry

00:20:04.830 --> 00:20:08.160
were just as consistent
as Euclid's flat geometry.

00:20:08.160 --> 00:20:10.380
That is, if there were any inconsistencies

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:12.630
in hyperbolic or spherical geometry,

00:20:12.630 --> 00:20:16.323
then they must also be present
in Euclid's flat geometry.

00:20:17.190 --> 00:20:20.400
The prospects for these new
geometries were looking great.

00:20:20.400 --> 00:20:23.850
And it turns out, this
was just the beginning.

00:20:23.850 --> 00:20:24.683
(soft music)

00:20:24.683 --> 00:20:28.380
In 1905, Einstein proposed the
special theory of relativity,

00:20:28.380 --> 00:20:30.780
which is based on just two postulates.

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:32.550
One, "The laws of physics are the same

00:20:32.550 --> 00:20:34.830
in all inertial frames of reference."

00:20:34.830 --> 00:20:37.380
And two, "The speed of light in a vacuum

00:20:37.380 --> 00:20:40.440
is the same for all inertial observers."

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:45.003
So, as a result, space
and time must be relative.

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:49.140
But that created a problem
for Newtonian gravity,

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:50.790
because, according to Newton,

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:53.280
the force of gravity is
inversely proportional

00:20:53.280 --> 00:20:56.070
to the distance between
the two objects squared.

00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:58.080
But in Einstein's special relativity,

00:20:58.080 --> 00:21:01.140
that distance is no longer well-defined.

00:21:01.140 --> 00:21:03.840
In whose reference frame are we measuring?

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:07.020
And so Einstein had to
find a way to reconcile

00:21:07.020 --> 00:21:09.420
relativity and gravity.

00:21:09.420 --> 00:21:11.310
Two years later, in 1907,

00:21:11.310 --> 00:21:14.340
Einstein had the happiest
thought of his life,

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:17.280
he imagined a man falling
off the roof of a house.

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:19.050
And what made Einstein so joyful

00:21:19.050 --> 00:21:21.480
is that he realized that
while the man is falling,

00:21:21.480 --> 00:21:23.820
he would feel absolutely weightless,

00:21:23.820 --> 00:21:25.320
and if he let go of an object,

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:29.010
it would just remain in
uniform motion relative to him.

00:21:29.010 --> 00:21:33.210
It would be just like being
in space, not near any masses,

00:21:33.210 --> 00:21:36.210
floating around in a spaceship
at constant velocity.

00:21:36.210 --> 00:21:39.210
And that is an inertial observer.

00:21:39.210 --> 00:21:41.040
Now, here's the big breakthrough,

00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:43.590
Einstein realized that
they're not just similar,

00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:45.120
they are identical,

00:21:45.120 --> 00:21:47.250
because there is no
experiment you could do

00:21:47.250 --> 00:21:49.200
to determine whether you're in free fall

00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:51.180
in a uniform gravitational field,

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:52.950
or whether you are in deep space,

00:21:52.950 --> 00:21:55.083
not near any massive objects.

00:21:56.160 --> 00:21:58.410
And so the free-falling man too

00:21:58.410 --> 00:22:00.330
must be an inertial observer,

00:22:00.330 --> 00:22:02.340
meaning he is not accelerating,

00:22:02.340 --> 00:22:05.970
and he's not experiencing
any force of gravity.

00:22:05.970 --> 00:22:08.040
But if gravity is not a force,

00:22:08.040 --> 00:22:09.300
then how do you explain things

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:11.550
like the space station orbiting Earth?

00:22:11.550 --> 00:22:14.550
Shouldn't it just fly
off in a straight line?

00:22:14.550 --> 00:22:18.000
Well, astronauts in the space
station also feel weightless.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.350
And that's the key,

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:22.380
it feels just as if they're
traveling at constant velocity

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:23.910
in a straight line.

00:22:23.910 --> 00:22:25.020
It feels like that

00:22:25.020 --> 00:22:27.570
because that's precisely
what they're doing,

00:22:27.570 --> 00:22:30.030
they're traveling in a straight line.

00:22:30.030 --> 00:22:32.280
How, then, could that
straight line appear curved

00:22:32.280 --> 00:22:34.170
to a distant observer?

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:35.003
The answer is,

00:22:35.003 --> 00:22:38.913
because the space time that
straight line is on is curved.

00:22:40.650 --> 00:22:43.440
See, massive objects curve spacetime,

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:45.510
and objects moving
through curved spacetime

00:22:45.510 --> 00:22:48.780
will follow the shortest path
through that curved geometry,

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:50.070
the geodesic.

00:22:50.070 --> 00:22:51.810
So, while astronauts in the space station

00:22:51.810 --> 00:22:53.460
are following a straight line,

00:22:53.460 --> 00:22:55.710
it appears curved to a distant observer

00:22:55.710 --> 00:22:58.953
because the Earth curves
the spacetime around it.

00:23:00.690 --> 00:23:03.900
So, the behavior of straight
lines in curved geometries

00:23:03.900 --> 00:23:07.170
is core to understanding
the universe we live in.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:09.810
And in the more than a hundred
years since it was published,

00:23:09.810 --> 00:23:11.400
the general theory of relativity

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:14.481
has been remarkably successful.

00:23:14.481 --> 00:23:15.314
(soft music)

00:23:15.314 --> 00:23:18.690
In 2014, astronomers briefly
observed a supernova,

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:22.170
a violent and extremely
bright death of a star.

00:23:22.170 --> 00:23:24.300
In fact, they saw the exact same supernova

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:26.520
in four different places.

00:23:26.520 --> 00:23:27.480
How?

00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:29.610
Well, in between the supernova and earth,

00:23:29.610 --> 00:23:33.060
there was a massive galaxy,
which curved space time,

00:23:33.060 --> 00:23:34.440
so light from the supernova,

00:23:34.440 --> 00:23:36.510
which was spreading out in all directions,

00:23:36.510 --> 00:23:39.330
had several different
paths to reach the earth,

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:40.830
and four of those reached Earth

00:23:40.830 --> 00:23:42.780
at approximately the same time.

00:23:42.780 --> 00:23:47.220
The galaxy had functioned as
a massive gravitational lens.

00:23:47.220 --> 00:23:50.250
The astronomers realized that
other galaxies in the cluster

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:53.160
might also lens the light
from that supernova,

00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:54.750
but with different path lengths

00:23:54.750 --> 00:23:56.400
and gravitational potentials,

00:23:56.400 --> 00:24:00.000
so the light would reach
earth at different times.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:01.500
After careful modeling,

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:03.960
they predicted that
they should see a replay

00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:06.573
of that supernova just a year later.

00:24:07.650 --> 00:24:10.020
And on the 11th of December, 2015,

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:14.163
just as predicted, they saw
the same supernova once more.

00:24:15.870 --> 00:24:17.940
In addition to being able
to observe the effects

00:24:17.940 --> 00:24:19.290
of curved spacetime,

00:24:19.290 --> 00:24:22.590
we can now even measure the
ripples of space time itself,

00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:25.230
