seems to be buzzing

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:38.880
with the remnants of grand cosmic events.

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:41.760
In the hundred years since
general relativity was published,

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:44.310
countless findings have
supported its predictions,

00:24:44.310 --> 00:24:47.610
and at its very core are
the curved geometries

00:24:47.610 --> 00:24:49.980
of Bolyai and Riemann.

00:24:49.980 --> 00:24:52.080
But so far, all the
effects we've looked at

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:54.753
are local distortions of spacetime.

00:24:55.590 --> 00:24:58.303
What is the shape of the entire universe?

00:24:58.303 --> 00:25:00.055
(stars whooshing)

00:25:00.055 --> 00:25:00.888
(contemplative music)

00:25:00.888 --> 00:25:02.790
Using the differences
between the geometries,

00:25:02.790 --> 00:25:04.920
we can find that out too.

00:25:04.920 --> 00:25:06.090
In flat geometry,

00:25:06.090 --> 00:25:08.160
we expect all the angles of a triangle

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:11.160
to add up to 180 degrees without fail.

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:12.720
But in spherical geometry,

00:25:12.720 --> 00:25:16.530
the angles don't add up to
180 degrees, but to more.

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:18.390
Similarly in hyperbolic geometry,

00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:21.660
the angles add up to
less than 180 degrees.

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:24.180
So, to determine the
shape of the universe,

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:27.480
you just need to measure
the angles of a triangle.

00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:30.360
And measuring a triangle is
precisely what Gauss was doing

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:31.830
200 years ago.

00:25:31.830 --> 00:25:33.990
In fact, this led some to speculate

00:25:33.990 --> 00:25:35.970
that he was actually trying
to measure the curvature

00:25:35.970 --> 00:25:37.950
of space itself.

00:25:37.950 --> 00:25:39.780
The angle he found,

00:25:39.780 --> 00:25:42.573
180 degrees, within observational error.

00:25:43.770 --> 00:25:46.170
But that shouldn't be very surprising.

00:25:46.170 --> 00:25:49.830
Take this balloon, for example,
which approximates a sphere.

00:25:49.830 --> 00:25:52.500
If I draw a small triangle on it,

00:25:52.500 --> 00:25:55.290
well, the surface I'm
drawing on is basically flat,

00:25:55.290 --> 00:25:56.790
so the angles inside the triangle

00:25:56.790 --> 00:25:59.700
will add up to essentially 180 degrees.

00:25:59.700 --> 00:26:02.850
Only if I make the triangle large enough

00:26:02.850 --> 00:26:05.970
will the effects of
curvature come into play,

00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:07.620
and then the angles in the triangle

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.110
will add up to more than 180 degrees.

00:26:10.110 --> 00:26:12.174
And this was the problem
with Gauss' experiment,

00:26:12.174 --> 00:26:14.850
even if he was trying
to measure the curvature

00:26:14.850 --> 00:26:18.240
of space itself, for which
there is no solid evidence,

00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:21.240
the triangle he measured
would've been far too small

00:26:21.240 --> 00:26:24.472
relative to the size of the universe.

00:26:24.472 --> 00:26:25.305
(ball thudding)

00:26:25.305 --> 00:26:26.138
(soft music)

00:26:26.138 --> 00:26:28.170
So, in order to overcome the scale issue

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:29.460
that Gauss encountered,

00:26:29.460 --> 00:26:32.220
we need to scale the triangles
formed between mountains

00:26:32.220 --> 00:26:34.860
up to the largest triangles we can.

00:26:34.860 --> 00:26:37.050
And since looking further and further away

00:26:37.050 --> 00:26:39.540
is the same as looking
further back in time,

00:26:39.540 --> 00:26:42.390
we need to look back as far as possible,

00:26:42.390 --> 00:26:45.210
to the very first light we can see,

00:26:45.210 --> 00:26:48.420
the Cosmic Microwave Background, or CMB,

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:52.923
a picture from when the universe
was just 380,000 years old.

00:26:53.790 --> 00:26:56.640
While the CMB is almost
completely uniform,

00:26:56.640 --> 00:27:00.300
there are some spots that are
slightly hotter or colder.

00:27:00.300 --> 00:27:02.910
Now, we know how far away the CMB is,

00:27:02.910 --> 00:27:06.060
so if we can figure out
how large such a spot is,

00:27:06.060 --> 00:27:09.570
then we can draw a cosmic triangle.

00:27:09.570 --> 00:27:11.280
It's thought that the first density

00:27:11.280 --> 00:27:12.510
and temperature variations

00:27:12.510 --> 00:27:14.910
originated from quantum fluctuations

00:27:14.910 --> 00:27:16.560
in the very early universe,

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:19.590
which were then blown up
as the universe expanded.

00:27:19.590 --> 00:27:21.570
But due to this rapid expansion,

00:27:21.570 --> 00:27:25.590
not all regions were in causal
contact with each other.

00:27:25.590 --> 00:27:27.570
So, using the information we have

00:27:27.570 --> 00:27:29.520
of how the early universe evolved,

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:33.150
astronomers can predict how
often spots of different sizes

00:27:33.150 --> 00:27:35.790
should appear in the CMB.

00:27:35.790 --> 00:27:38.520
This is what this power spectrum shows,

00:27:38.520 --> 00:27:40.920
essentially a histogram of how often

00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:45.000
each spot size should occur
if the universe is flat.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.390
So now we have something to
compare our measurement to.

00:27:48.390 --> 00:27:49.740
If the universe is flat,

00:27:49.740 --> 00:27:51.120
the angle we measure on the sky

00:27:51.120 --> 00:27:53.550
should be the same as we'd expect.

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:55.770
But if the universe is
curved like a sphere,

00:27:55.770 --> 00:27:57.600
the angles of the triangle should add up

00:27:57.600 --> 00:28:00.000
to more than 180 degrees,

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:03.300
so the angle we'd measure
would be larger than predicted,

00:28:03.300 --> 00:28:05.880
and this peak would shift to the left.

00:28:05.880 --> 00:28:09.030
Similarly, if the universe
has hyperbolic geometry,

00:28:09.030 --> 00:28:11.700
then spots should appear
smaller than predicted,

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:14.520
and this peak would shift to the right.

00:28:14.520 --> 00:28:16.500
So, what do we measure?

00:28:16.500 --> 00:28:18.240
This is the data from the Plank mission,

00:28:18.240 --> 00:28:20.610
which is almost exactly what you'd expect

00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:22.530
if the universe were flat.

00:28:22.530 --> 00:28:24.960
This mission also gives us
the current best estimate

00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:26.490
for the curvature of the universe,

00:28:26.490 --> 00:28:31.490
which is 0.0007, plus minus 0.0019.

00:28:31.830 --> 00:28:35.730
So that's basically zero
within the margin of error.

00:28:35.730 --> 00:28:37.020
So we're fairly certain

00:28:37.020 --> 00:28:39.453
that the universe we live in is flat.

00:28:42.120 --> 00:28:43.590
But living in a flat universe

00:28:43.590 --> 00:28:45.531
seems to be remarkably serendipitous.

00:28:45.531 --> 00:28:46.364
